# match for multi-branch conditionals

## Rule

When the **same expression** is compared against **multiple discrete alternatives**, use **`match`** instead of **`if` / `elif`** when you would otherwise write **`if`** plus **two or more `elif`** (**three or more** branches on that discriminant). This matches “more than two conditions” on the same value before a final `else`.

```python
# ❌ Avoid — same discriminant, many elifs
if status == "pending":
    ...
elif status == "running":
    ...
elif status == "done":
    ...
elif status == "failed":
    ...

# ✅ Prefer
match status:
    case "pending":
        ...
    case "running":
        ...
    case "done":
        ...
    case "failed":
        ...
```

## When not to force match

- **Unrelated predicates** (`if a > 0`, `elif b is None`)—`match` is not a readability win; keep `if`/`elif` or split logic.
- **Ranges or inequalities**—use `if`/`elif` or map to a discriminant first, then `match`.
- **Python 3.9 or older** targets—this project uses **3.13**, so `match` is available.

## Enum / sealed-style types

Prefer **`match`** on **`Enum`** members or small literal sets; use **`case _`** (or exhaustiveness checks) for defaults instead of a long final `else`.
